################ Setup for Terminating Gateway #########################################
Install Consul and Envoy ( I have used Consul v1.21.5 and Envoy 1.32.2 )
https://www.envoyproxy.io/docs/envoy/latest/start/install 
I have used multipass here.

Run Consul:
consul agent -dev

Step 1: Start an "External" Service
python3 -m http.server 9001

Step 2: Register the External Service in the Catalog
Since this service is "outside" the mesh, we register it directly to the Consul catalog rather than through an agent.

Create external-service.json:

{
  "Node": "external-node",
  "Address": "127.0.0.1",
  "Service": {
    "ID": "legacy-app-1",
    "Service": "legacy-app",
    "Port": 9001
  }
}

Register it:
curl --request PUT --data @external-service.json localhost:8500/v1/catalog/register

Step 3: Create the Terminating Gateway Configuration
Now, tell Consul which services this gateway is allowed to represent.
Create terminating-gateway.hcl:

Kind = "terminating-gateway"
Name = "my-terminating-gateway"
Services = [
  {
    Name = "legacy-app"
  }
]

Write the config entry:
consul config write terminating-gateway.hcl

Step 4: Start the Gateway Process
In a new terminal, launch the Envoy proxy that will act as the Gateway. Consul will automatically generate the Envoy bootstrap config for you.

consul connect envoy -gateway=terminating -service my-terminating-gateway -register

Step 5: Test Connectivity from a Mesh Service
To prove it works, we’ll register a "test-client" and try to reach the legacy app through its allocated local port.

Register a client with an upstream:
Create test-client.json:

{
  "service": {
    "name": "test-client",
    "connect": {
      "sidecar_service": {
        "proxy": {
          "upstreams": [{
            "destination_name": "legacy-app",
            "local_bind_port": 1234
          }]
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

Register and start its sidecar:
consul services register test-client.json
consul connect envoy -sidecar-for test-client -admin-bind "127.0.0.1:19001" &

Curl the upstream:
curl localhost:1234

#########################  Setup for Service Router, Splitter and Resolver #######################
Flow : Router -> Splitter -> Resolver
The Scenario
We will set up a service called web that talks to a backend service called api. We will simulate two versions of api: v1 (stable) and v2 (canary).
/v1 -> api v1 
/v2 -> api v2
/distribute -> 50% to v1 and 50% to v2
/ -> external service accessed through terminating gateway

Step 1: Register Two Versions of the Backend
Register two instances of the api service with different metadata so Consul can distinguish them.

api-v1.json

{
  "service": {
    "name": "api",
    "id": "api-v1",
    "meta": { "version": "v1" },
    "port": 8081,
    "connect": { "sidecar_service": {} }
  }
}

api-v2.json

{
  "service": {
    "name": "api",
    "id": "api-v2",
    "meta": { "version": "v2" },
    "port": 8082,
    "connect": { "sidecar_service": {} }
  }
}
Register both: 
consul services register api-v1.json 
consul services register api-v2.json

Step 2: Define the Service Resolver (Grouping)
The Resolver creates "subsets" based on the metadata we just added. This is the foundation for splitting traffic.

api-resolver.hcl

Kind = "service-resolver"
Name = "api"

Subsets = {
  "v1" = {
    Filter = "Service.Meta.version == v1"
  }
  "v2" = {
    Filter = "Service.Meta.version == v2"
  }
}

Apply: consul config write api-resolver.hcl

Step 3: Define the Service Splitter (Weighting)
The Splitter tells Consul how much traffic to send to each subset defined in the Resolver.

api-splitter.hcl

Kind = "service-splitter"
Name = "api"

Splits = [
  {
    Weight        = 50
    ServiceSubset = "v1"
  },
  {
    Weight        = 50
    ServiceSubset = "v2"
  }
]
Apply: consul config write api-splitter.hcl

Step 4: Define the Service Router (Path-based Routing)
The Router is the first stop in the chain. It can send traffic to different services or splitters based on HTTP attributes like the URL path.

api-router.hcl

Kind = "service-router"
Name = "api"

Routes = [
  {
    Match {
      HTTP {
        PathPrefix = "/v1"
      }
    }
    Destination {
      ServiceSubset = "v1"
      PrefixRewrite = "/"  # This strips /v1 and sends / to the app
    }
  },
  {
    Match {
      HTTP {
        PathPrefix = "/v2"
      }
    }
    Destination {
      ServiceSubset = "v2"
      PrefixRewrite = "/"  # This strips /v2 and sends / to the app
    }
  },
  {
    Match {
      HTTP {
        PathPrefix = "/distribute"
      }
    }
    Destination {
      Service       = "api"
      PrefixRewrite = "/"  # This strips /distribute and sends / to the app
    }
  },
  {
    Match {
      HTTP {
        PathPrefix = "/" 
      }
    }
    Destination {
      Service = "legacy-app"
    }
  }
]

Apply: consul config write api-router.hcl

Step 5: Start the Client and Test
Register a client:

{
  "service": {
    "name": "web",
    "connect": {
      "sidecar_service": {
        "proxy": {
          "upstreams": [{"destination_name": "api", "local_bind_port": 5000}]
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

Start the proxies:
Launch Envoy proxies for api-v1, api-v2, and web.

# Sidecar for v1
consul connect envoy -sidecar-for api-v1 -admin-bind 127.0.0.1:19005 &
# Sidecar for v2
consul connect envoy -sidecar-for api-v2 -admin-bind 127.0.0.1:19006 &
# Sidecar for web (the client)
consul connect envoy -sidecar-for web -admin-bind 127.0.0.1:19007 &

Run application api v1 on 8081:-

cd api-v1
touch api-v1-test
python3 -m http.server 8081

Run application api v2 on 8082:-

cd api-v2
touch api-v2-test
python3 -m http.server 8082

Step 6: Create proxy-defaults.hcl

Kind      = "proxy-defaults"
Name      = "global"
Config {
  protocol = "http"
}

consul config write proxy-default.hcl 

Step 7: Validation
curl localhost:5000/v1
curl localhost:5000/v2
curl localhost:5000/distribute
curl localhost:5000
